In France, voting has traditionally been a little technical experience: voters isolate themselves in a cabin and insert in an envelope a paper sheet printed in advance indicating which candidate they have chosen.
After the officials check the voter’s identity, he leaves the envelope in the ballot box and signs the voting list.
The French electoral law codifies the procedures to be followed.
Since 1988, ballots must be transparent, so that voters and observers confirm that there are no envelopes at the beginning of the vote and that envelopes are not added except for those of the voters who are duly counted.
Candidates can send their representatives to witness at all stages of the process. In the evening, the votes are counted by volunteers under strict supervision, in compliance with clear procedures.
